THIRD-PARTY COMPONENTS AND THE ffmpeg / x264 (GPL) BOUNDARY

The transcoder (crate `transcoder`, milestone M4) invokes `ffmpeg` and
`ffprobe` as SEPARATE, SERVER-SIDE PROCESSES on the self-hoster's own
hardware. It does not statically or dynamically link any GPL-licensed
media library into the proprietary Software, and the distributed Apple
client binaries (iOS/tvOS) contain NO ffmpeg, libx264, or other GPL
code. Clients receive standard HLS (an MPEG-TS/fMP4 byte stream) over
the network; the GPL-covered code never crosses into a distributed
proprietary binary. The process/network boundary between the
proprietary Software and the separately-obtained ffmpeg binary is an
arms-length boundary, not a derivative work.

The ffmpeg binary itself is NOT distributed as part of this Software.
In the reference deployment it is supplied at container-build time from
a third-party image (`mwader/static-ffmpeg`), whose own GPL terms apply
to that binary and bind whoever distributes that image — not this
Software's proprietary license. Self-hosting operators are responsible
for the license terms of any ffmpeg build they supply.

Build guidance to keep this boundary clean:

  - The copy / remux transcode path uses NO video encoder (stream copy
    only) and therefore pulls in no x264/x265 GPL encoder at all.
  - Where re-encoding is required, prefer hardware encoders
    (VideoToolbox / NVENC / QSV / VAAPI) or an LGPL ffmpeg build; only
    fall back to a `--enable-gpl` (libx264) build when no alternative
    encoder is available, and only on the server side.
  - Never bundle, statically link, or ship libx264/libx265 inside an
    App Store client binary.

This is the project's standing engineering posture. A formal
component-license review should accompany the first App Store
submission (M2). See docs/M4-TRANSCODE-VERIFICATION.md for the
transcoder's runtime model.
